vectorData.altText: That’s right! The fibrous layer of periosteum is superficial to the cellular layer. This layer is made up of dense irregular CT. It functions in ligament and tendon attachment.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

superficial fibrous layer is dense irregular CT: collagen type I, produced by fibrocytes, form a dense CT capsule that attaches bone to other structures, such as skeletal muscle, tendon, or ligament
2. deep cellular (osteogenic) layer: consists of osteoprogenitor cells, osteoblasts, bone-
    lining cells and osteoclasts; fxns in bone growth, repair & remodeling

In the images to the left, the dense irregular CT of the periosteum blends with the dense irregular CT of the epimysium surrounding a skeletal muscle, thus attaching muscle to bone. Collagen type I fibres of the periosteum blend with collagen type I fibres of superficial circumferential osteons and are cemented there into the bone matrix; these are called perforating or Sharpey’s fibres, and are more robust at points of ligament or tendon attachment, where tensile forces are greatest.
